column1: New Delhi, Feb 16 (ANI) - On the fifth anniversary of India's national day on February 16, the country will mark the occasion of the centenary of the Indian Independence movement, Indian Chief Minister Arvind Kejriwal said during his visit to New Delhi.

There is a lot of significance to be celebrated in this historic year. The national day would be celebrated for the first time in the country's history and it would mark a new era, as well as the milestone of modernisation, the creation of the modernised India and the opening of new frontier. This is very significant for the 21st century and for Indian people, Kejriwal said during his speech at the Jawaharlal Nehru University (JNU) campus here on Saturday.
For the sixth anniversary of the Independence movement, the event will be celebrated on India's national day.

We are going to commemorate the anniversary of independence - India's national day is the centenary. The centenary celebrations in India, which marks the anniversary of India's independence, will be celebrated as a celebration, he said.

Echoing Prime Minister Narendra Modi's words of 15 years ago, Kejriwal said that despite "great disappointment" over "the slow economic recovery", the situation on the ground has improved significantly in the last decade, while the number of people of all classes in the country have increased.

In one year, more than 200 crore people have gotten job as per the government statistics, and even more workers have moved out of the labour force in the last 10 years. The economic growth in the last decade is much more than the growth seen in the last 10 years. I have personally witnessed such progress. The numbers of the unemployed have also decreased in the last 10 years. If you add all this up, it gives an impression of an improvement in development of the country, he said.
Kejriwal praised the Prime Minister who has launched the Right To Education (RTE) and introduced the Bharat Ratna education reform which would enable children and workers to become literate.
For the seventh anniversary of the independence of the country, the event would be celebrated in two parts: in Delhi and in Karnataka.

I believe that with this, we will also celebrate the other part, a lot of importance being given to the people of India in terms of their achievements as individuals. I know the Prime Minister will be celebrating with me in India, he said.
He said the government is taking up the issue of the National Day on the National Constitution Day (NCD) in this regard, also with the help of the state governments and the Centre.

column1: The Environmental Protection Agency announced Wednesday that it has issued a preliminary determination that greenhouse gas emissions for the construction industry were below estimates when they were first used in its 2011 draft report on energy efficiency standards for American buildings.
The draft EPA report was issued to help determine when new buildings must meet new regulations.
The agency's greenhouse gas assessment concluded:
Building systems, materials, and infrastructure that are less than compliant may significantly reduce or avoid GHG emissions at the construction site.

The EPA's draft report has not yet been finalized by the Office of Management and Budget, and that's likely to be a key sticking point in a dispute over what kind of regulations building and energy efficiency standards should adopt.

The Environmental Protection Agency's draft report was issued to help determine when new buildings must meet new regulations. The draft EPA report has not yet been finalized by the Office of Management and Budget, and that's likely to be a key sticking point in a dispute over what kind of regulations building and energy efficiency standards should adopt.

The Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research released analysis of EPA's greenhouse gas emissions estimates and found a positive overall trend for the construction sector as a whole. Overall, estimates of greenhouse gas emissions for the energy sector increased 2% from 2012 to 2013, compared to an 0% increase for the transportation sector.

An increase in greenhouse gas emissions from the construction industry accounted for 6% of all emissions from the energy sector from 2012 to 2013, according to an analysis of EPA's draft draft environmental impact statement. The results were in line with analysis by the Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research conducted on behalf of the Environmental Defense Fund.

But those estimates were a tiny fraction of the greenhouse gas emissions of the other energy industries. A National Bureau of Economic Research analysis showed that the overall carbon footprint of non-manufacturing, non-energy sector fossil fuel-based industries was 14.5 billion metric tons from 2010 to 2015, or nearly three times that of construction. The analysis suggested that construction and oil, gas and coal companies would each contribute as much as 5.1% of total climate pollution emissions.

In order to help you make some decisions, I want to give you some ideas on what makes a good book. If you have any suggestions for books, I would love to hear them!
If you don't know where to start, I can explain it in two simple steps:
1. The main character must understand why their actions are bad, and he must have reason for acting.
2. The main character must make choices for his future/future self which could lead him to regret his decision or to accept that he didn't do it.
3. The main character must have some way of explaining why he made the decision.

Hong Kong and the mainland both remain under martial law.

The People's Republic of China, which is not governed by Chinese authorities, also has some limitations on foreign travel and the Hong Kong special administrative region of the city is still under martial law.
The latest statistics released by the Hong Kong government show that 11,000 people died from starvation since 1949 and a record amount were murdered during the Chinese civil war.

At least 1,100 Hong Kongers, mainly farmers and labourers, have been executed since 1949 because of their association with outlawed pro-democracy groups or those advocating independence from China, the government said.
Hong Kong's leader Lee Teng-hui said on Thursday that Hong Kong remained committed to upholding democracy.
But he admitted that the mainland's policies of economic pressure were having an effect on Hong Kong's economy and could mean it no longer has "its own destiny".
For us the only way to bring about change is to use economic force.... If it (economic pressure) does not work then we will have to look for other alternatives.
Lee added that the Hong Kong government hoped the mainland would continue to implement reforms to the city's political system and legal system.
He said there was no question that the Communist party's central committee would be held next month.
At the weekend, the Chinese foreign ministry called on Hong Kong "to respect political reform and abide by basic rights and duties".
The government is deeply concerned by some recent developments in Hong Kong, said China's foreign ministry spokeswoman Hua Chunying.

We hope all parties, including the government in Hong Kong and the people there, can work through the relevant process to resolve the issue appropriately and without affecting or harming people in Hong Kong.
Last weekend, Hong Kong was divided into a zone of autonomy and a special administrative region, the People's Republic of China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
But the new status was only formalised on Wednesday, as the main political authority of the region was replaced by a council of Chinese nationals, including former Hong Kong lawmakers.
A special committee was also created on Hong Kong's border with China to carry out regular police and judicial checks.

Aussie-born entrepreneur Andrew Waugh wants to find a way to give farmers what they ask for. He set up Animal Crossing in 2009 and has since worked on games such as Doodle God.
At a press event yesterday Mr Waugh said Australians were becoming increasingly reluctant to engage with animals.

'I think we've all thought that we can take our dogs for walks. It might be fun to go to Disneyworld but don't expect to get a good photograph of them doing so with their arms in their pockets,' he told the Canberra Times.
'I think, in the US, I think it used to be an Australian thing, now people are just a little bit afraid of talking about animals' Andrew Waugh
It seems to be a bit old-fashioned at the moment for people to want to see a dog or have pictures taken with a dog. There is really not much interest in animals these days, especially on TV.
In its current state, Animal Crossing has only two animals - a horse and a sheep. However, it's become a major success and has been downloaded more than a million times.
In an effort to give farmers what they asked for, the game team put some of its key elements through their paces and looked for new ways to make the meat move around on a pet's body.

'If you give up a bit of animal control, we had a little bit of leeway because we had animals we could shoot with a rifle, like we've done for years now in some places, for example in New Zealand,' Mr Waugh said.

'We've had some bad reactions, but what we're really aiming for is just that the animal just has to get used to it, to feel comfortable and, you know, just feel at home with the animal itself, and there is a lot of animal interaction.
'What we really wanted to do is make it a little bit more interactive for some people and just give them something more physical interaction.
'We've never had animals this close to our game, it just feels like this is our animal and we're doing it because of that.
'It's a really exciting thing for us to do, it feels as if we're being approached as a human, as a community rather than as just a game, so we had to explore that, and we think that's fantastic.
'In fact, at the moment we have almost 500,000 Animal Crossing characters, so if we had had an average of 30% fewer, we'd have probably sold 1 million, or maybe a billion, in three or four years.'

column4: What its like to live with face blindness? A video produced for the BBC's The Project shows what it's like to see a person with severe or permanent facial blindness:

column1: When a person with face blindness finds he or she can no longer see with their left eye, the left eye is the only person the blind person recognizes.
These individuals are called 'focal line blind'.

Once they realize they cannot see normally, a person with focal line blindness will often lose their ability to see even more severely. A person with focal line blindness may also lose the ability to see normal everyday objects, like a map or window. It's possible to walk with this disorder and never realize it until it's too late.
An inability to see faces of people around you.
An inability to identify objects that they might recognize on the street or in the yard.
An inability to distinguish a person from an object they see.
An inability to recognize the shape of a face without the aid of visual acuity.

The first step is for a person with focal line blindness to try a new language. If this doesn't work, they may want to have a different kind of training or be sent to an office. Facial vision studies, such as Face Identification Test, are typically conducted in hospitals or schools with a trained facial examiner.

If all else fails, a person can have a procedure done to get the right eye to see properly. This may include procedures like retinal transplants, where a lens is removed to allow a person's right eye to see properly when trying to identify objects, or to increase the pupil size in their left eye to make the left eye more able to see more clearly.

People with focal line blindness are often at increased risk for death, and in the United States as a whole, more people are dying from Alzheimer's disease. This might explain why there hasn't been a treatment for the condition on the market for quite a while: Although it has an impact in the short term, many patients will live decades longer without this disorder.

column1: Two teenage girls had their life saved yesterday after a woman who claimed she had seen her daughter die from cervical cancer called local emergency services and asked if they could treat her mother.

The girl, aged 15, suffered severe internal bleeding, had lost her hair and was severely anaesthetised. Her mother, from the town of Northcote, said she was "absolutely devastated" by the incident. She said: "I have been through all the traumas and all the things I would want from my daughter. Now I just need to be able to take it all home with me. I think I have enough right now. I don't know how I am going to cope when my daughter wakes up at 4 am."

A spokesman for the county's health board confirmed the girl, who had not been named, was the youngest of three siblings. She was admitted to the hospital yesterday after suffering serious internal bleeding, with one of her legs removed and her face and skull fractured.

According to her mother, the girl's blood pressure was in the top 10 per cent of those in the entire Tasmanian town. "We have been through so much. We live in a very rural community in Northcote with no schools, no cars, no opportunities, no jobs," she said.

The girl's father, aged 39, from the town of Northcote, claimed he had met with the local chief constable three times for support. "The chief constable came to town and told me about the girl's plight and his concern about her health. It was his personal commitment that saved her life." He added: "The girl is recovering well and her condition is expected to improve after surgery tomorrow.

Earlier yesterday, a member of the public, who identified herself as David, posted on Facebook the news he'd heard the week before, and wrote: "This is the third time our 13 year old daughter has taken her life after she lost her hair, head and face."
The girl's friend told WA Now she had no idea the girl had been diagnosed with cervical cancer. She said: "I saw pictures of her being admitted to hospital this morning after her body had bled out."

The girl told the police that her dad came into her room and told her, "I know you have cancer, I'm sorry if I hurt you but it's not cancer because they're not the same thing. He claimed the second offence was not sexual assault as he was not married, but a sex offender.
Ryan had argued that his sexual conduct with young boys was justified on the grounds it was "necessary and reasonable" to ensure public safety.
His appeal was based on one of the four amendments which were included in the original legislation.
He wrote in his majority decision: "A majority of these appellants have failed to demonstrate that they are guilty of the offences against which they seek to challenge.
The Court is therefore of the view that the appellants are 'genuinely disadvantaged' in their ability to bring these three convictions to be heard in the Federal Court.
The Federal Court granted Ryan's appeal last year after hearing evidence that Ryan knew the girl who he allegedly abused when she was under 18.
A forensic assessment by police discovered that DNA from Ryan's blood was on her body when he was charged with the crimes.
Ryan, who had been denied parole by the Federal Court after the death penalty was ruled unconstitutional, pleaded guilty to the sexual activity with the child.
He was sentenced to 25 years to life, but his life sentences were only due to end when the court heard evidence of another child from his past had been born.
Kevin Nettles QC, for the State of Queensland, said Ryan should be allowed to serve his whole term at home after a new defence motion was accepted.
The Court recognises that there is a question whether Mr Ryan may qualify for some type of release under section 3 of the Sex Offenders Amendment Act 1974, he said.
It also recognises that no final decision has been made on this application.

column1: When to Check a Grant's Status

When the government grants a grant, many important information should be checked during the year. First, the Department of Finance is usually notified. The Department's website allows you to view all grants issued by the department that are currently being considered. If you have any questions, contact the department by phone at 04000 671 250.

The department is a registered charity that is run by the state government. The Department of Finance is a statutory body for the State Government, and is responsible for providing grants and loans from the Treasury to Commonwealth banks. The government has not provided a way of telling you how much funds have been funded and is unaware of the cost to the state of a grant. The Department's website offers many ways of checking grant status. You may need to send a letter to the department at any time, but there is no cost to you if you email the department.

The Department's website does not show grant status in a detailed way, and a grant's status cannot be changed until you can contact the department and fill out an enquiry form. It will require you to provide information about the grant, but it is not always useful in determining how much funds have been funded.
A detailed grant status report includes information about:
the period and date of the grant, and
the total amount of grants in any given fiscal year.
To see a copy of this report, or to request one, please contact the department by phone at 04000 671 250 or email Grant Status
The Department of Finance may also be able to give specific information about a grant. This can help with your decision about whether or not you can trust the Department's financial statements.
Grant Status and the Department of Finance

The Department of Finance receives a number of applications each year and is committed to meeting the needs of families in times of financial difficulty. There is no cost to you if you email the department to request grant status information.

It will tell the story of her two years in hospital, a difficult but rewarding road from trauma to recovery.
That was my hope for it, says Dylan. "To have a few years to get all the different parts done before I can move into acting."
She's been in the process of planning this film for three and a half years.
At the start she was worried that the director she worked with wouldn't be able to make time for her.
After spending more than five weeks on a phone call with the director, she was ready to commit to making it, she says.
But after making a few changes they were able to get the film going in 2013.
It started with a script by her former acting partner Robby Moulden, and it's been written with "everything I've learnt".
What I've learnt is that you never know - that there's no end point to the journey of a road film, Cerruth says.

When you think of the story of what happened that night, the way it was written that night, the emotional weight that was imposed on everyone involved - even after they passed away, for them to say that that's why they never got the chance to do what they wanted to do - it's just shocking.

It breaks your heart because the director didn't have the power to tell people what to expect."
The rest of the team include fellow castmates Matthew McConaughey as Shane, Mark Strong as the journalist and Lisa-Marie Roberts as the medical assistant to help with the recovery.
A video for a song by The Stranglers will be played at the launch of the film.
